Using the full household roster (youll need to go back the full raw data source, 21600-0001-Data.dta), create the following variables for each respondent. Document any decisions that you make regarding missing values, definitions, etc. in your narrative as well as in the R code. Include a frequency tabulation and a histogram of each result.

# download file from URL; unzip and load
tmp <- Sys.getenv("TMPDIR")

download.file(
  url="http://staff.washington.edu/phurvitz/csde502_winter_2021/data/21600-0001-Data.dta.zip",
  destfile= file.path(tmp, "21600-0001-Data.dta.zip", fsep=""))

ah <- read_dta(unz(file.path(tmp, "21600-0001-Data.dta.zip", fsep=""), filename="21600-0001-Data.dta"))

1.1

Total number in household

I used the first question for each household member to count the number in the household. For each question, if participants marked a 7 for legitimate skip (they didnt have another member of their household), I did not add to the count. If participants did not mark 7, I added to the count of household members until they marked 7.

hhmem <- ah %>%
    select(AID, H1HR2A, H1HR2B, H1HR2C, H1HR2D, H1HR2E, 
           H1HR2F, H1HR2G, H1HR2H, H1HR2I, H1HR2J, 
           H1HR2K, H1HR2L, H1HR2M, H1HR2N, H1HR2O, 
           H1HR2P, H1HR2Q, H1HR2R, H1HR2S, H1HR2T)

hhmem$counter <- 0
for (i in 2:21) {
    hhmem <- hhmem %>%
        mutate(counter = ifelse(hhmem[,i]==7, counter, counter+1))
}
hhsize <- data.frame(t(table(hhmem$counter))) %>%
    select(Var2, Freq) %>%
    rename(HHSize=Var2, Freq=Freq)

kable(hhsize)

2

What proportion of students live with two biological parents? Include the analysis in your R code.

parents <- ah %>%
    select(AID, H1HR3A, H1HR3B, H1HR3C, H1HR3D, H1HR3E, 
           H1HR3F, H1HR3G, H1HR3H, H1HR3I, H1HR3J, 
           H1HR3K, H1HR3L, H1HR3M, H1HR3N, H1HR3O, 
           H1HR3P, H1HR3Q, H1HR3R, H1HR3S, H1HR3T)
parents$biomom <- FALSE
parents$biodad <- FALSE
for (i in 2:21) {
    parents <- parents %>%
        mutate(biodad = ifelse(parents[,i]==11, TRUE, biodad)) %>%
        mutate(biomom = ifelse(parents[,i]==14, TRUE, biomom)) %>%
      mutate(bothparents = case_when(
        biodad==TRUE & biomom==TRUE ~ 1,
        biodad==FALSE | biomom==FALSE ~ 0
      ))
      
}

biopar <- data.frame(t(table(parents$bothparents))) %>%
  select(Var2, Freq) %>%
  rename(BothParents = Var2)

Share living with both parents = mean(parents$bothparents) = 0.64.

3

Calculate the number of household members that are NOT biological mother, biological father, full brother or full sister. Create a contingency table and histogram for this variable.

rels <- ah %>%
    select(AID, H1HR3A, H1HR3B, H1HR3C, H1HR3D, H1HR3E, 
           H1HR3F, H1HR3G, H1HR3H, H1HR3I, H1HR3J, 
           H1HR3K, H1HR3L, H1HR3M, H1HR3N, H1HR3O, 
           H1HR3P, H1HR3Q, H1HR3R, H1HR3S, H1HR3T)
rels$numothers <- 0
for (i in 2:21) {
    rels <- rels %>%
        mutate(numothers = ifelse(
          (parents[,i] != 8 & parents[,i] != 11 &
            parents[,i] != 5 & parents[,i] != 14 & 
            parents[,i] != 96 & parents[,i] != 97 &
            parents[,i] != 98), numothers+1, numothers
        ))
      
}
otherrel <- data.frame(t(table(rels$numothers))) %>%
    select(Var2, Freq) %>%
    rename(OtherRelatives=Var2, Freq=Freq)

kable(otherrel)
OtherRelatives Freq
0 4679
1 1103
2 391
3 154
4 89
5 45
6 22
7 9
8 5
9 3
10 1
11 2
12 1 
hist(rels$numothers)
